ays particular attention to the issue of land-use in his analysis of these failures of popular control in traditional city politics. Urban political institutions, however, are not just instruments for the dispensing of valued outcomes or devices for social problem-solving—they help to form the citizenry. Our present institutions largely define citizens as interest group adversaries and do little to encourage them to focus on the commercial public interest of the city. Elkin concludes by proposing new institutional arrangements that would be better able to harness the self-interested behavior of individuals for the common good of a commercial republic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMunicipal governmentzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acity, urban, metropolis, american culture, republic, democracy, political science, politicians, business, corruption, wealth, class, stratification, inequity, inequality, social justice, land use, interest groups, common good, commerce, capitalism, revenue, government, municipal, market, economy, bias, systemic racism, problem solving, judgment, selfishness, motivation, nonfiction, politics, philosophy, human nature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226301631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226301631/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles